>>48334675
>Review for Toons in Tinseltown (Ch1 & Ch2)
Posting it again because I don't know if people saw it.

It's a very good read and I can't wait to see more.

The description is great, the world building is well shown and I really want to see more. Especially in how toons go about business Hollywood style, maybe leaning into the darker aspects of Hollywood and the film industry.

The best part to me is Anon's inner dialogue. The way it captures his emotions is suburb and does really well to reveal a nervous man who, while not a complete wimp, is still new to the high life.

One glaring issue I have is the name of 'Anon Imos'.

It feels really out of place. The name 'Anon' to me is more suited for short form texts and I feel this story should go with a named protagonist instead. He really stands out amongst the other well-defined and described characters that it just feels off. Especially because he has a defined backstory and character. (this is a problem for many hmofa stories)

I also think you could lean into the 'toon' aspect a bit more, kind of like in Roger Rabbit. But, seeing how Anon walks a pink panther around, it's getting there.

Overall, good job. I'm excited to see more.

Think about it this way:
>you take your waifur to the zoo
>it's fun & going well until
>at the monkey house a chimp
>shits into its own hand
>then takes a big sniff and a taste
>you look at your waifur
>neither of you can unsee it
>and you will never unsee the look f disgust on her face

It's a bit circumstantial. Think of your reaction in that situation. If you happen to see one of your cousins at its worst, how would you feel? And, if your waifur with you right there watching it too, how would *that* make you feel?

So, if you and your pooch waifur are walking down the street and happen to see a dog eating its own shit, that's pretty much how I'd expect her to feel. Or maybe you and your kitty waifur are watching a movie when the cat walks in and proceeds to lick its own asshole clean. In perspective, you both know the difference between sapience and animals, while at the same there is a very uncomfortable zone of being reminded just how close we all are to our animal cousins.

You both need enough mental maturity to get over it and feel comfortable around each other without confusing the behavior of your animal cousins. On the flip side, animals are great company and can do so many cute things, too. Getting your cat to play with string is an opportunity to tease your kitty waifur.
